<TITLE> Europe shares stage broad rebound after Wall St bounce </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Feb 8 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - European shares rose early on Friday, paring some of this week's losses, ater a rebound on Wall Street and as a rally in crude oil helped energy stocks. Construction group Sacyr Vallehermoso rose 4.2 percent after a newspaper report that a French-backed group of banks and insurers were in talks to buy its one third stake in Eiffage. French construction group Lafarge rose 3.4 percent after a newspaper report said investment group GBL may raise its stake to 18 percent and possibly to 25 percent. The rise in crude oil futures to close to $89 a barrel helped push up shares in BP, Total and Royal Dutch Shell, which rose between 0.6 and 1.4 percent. By 0815 GMT the FTSEurofirst 300 index of top European shares rose 1.2 percent to 1,311.29 points. The index has fallen by nearly 4 percent this week as concern has grown about the outlook for the US economy, and analysts doubted any rally would be very long lived. "The market is becoming aware that the crisis in the United States will indeed have an adverse impact on growth in Europe," said Heino Ruland, a strategist at FrankfurtFinanz in Germany. Around Europe, London's FTSE 100 index rose 1 percent, while Frankfurt's DAX gained 1.2 percent and Paris' CAC 40 gained 1.1 perce
